> - **Topic:** Design and implement a lexical analyzer using C language to recognize all valid tokens in the input program, ignoring redundant spaces, tabs, newlines, and comments

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

A **Lexical Analyzer** (also called a **Scanner** or **Lexer**) is the **first phase of a compiler** whose primary task is to read the input source program character-by-character, group them into **lexemes**, and produce a stream of **tokens** as output. Each token is a pair consisting of a **token name** and an **optional attribute value** (such as a pointer to the symbol table entry).

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 2024 Definition (Aho-Sethi-Ullman Standard):**
> A **Token** is a classification of a lexeme (e.g., *identifier*, *keyword*, *operator*). A **Lexeme** is the actual character sequence matched by a token pattern. A **Pattern** is the rule that describes the set of lexemes corresponding to a token.

The lexer must also perform **secondary tasks**:
- Stripping out **comments** and **white spaces** (spaces, tabs, newlines).
- Correlating **error messages** with the source program line numbers.
- Communicating with the **Symbol Table Manager** to store identifiers.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Think of a **lexical analyzer** as a **postal sorting clerk at a regional hub**.

Imagine you are a clerk handling thousands of letters. You do **not** read the entire content of every letter. Instead, you:
1. Glance at the **envelope address** and **pincode** (these are like *identifiers* and *constants*).
2. Notice **stamps and markings** (like *keywords* such as "URGENT" or "REGISTERED").
3. Observe **special characters** like arrows and arrows on the envelope (like *operators* `+`, `-`, `*`, `/`).
4. **Discard wrapping paper, extra spaces, and advertisements** in the envelope (like ignoring *whitespace* and *comments*).
5. **Group the meaningful items** into standard categories and forward them to the next stage (the *parser*).

That is **exactly** what a lexical analyzer does with your C program. It does **not care about whether `int x = 5;` is a valid statement** — it just identifies `int` (keyword), `x` (identifier), `=` (operator), `5` (constant), `;` (symbol). Validation of structure is the **parser's** job.

## 1.3 KTU-Standard Token Categories

| # | Token Category | Examples | Pattern Rule |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | **Keywords** | `int`, `float`, `if`, `while`, `return` | Reserved words in the language |
| 2 | **Identifiers** | `x`, `sum`, `_count`, `var123` | Letter or `_` followed by letters/digits/`_` |
| 3 | **Constants / Numbers** | `123`, `45.67`, `0`, `9.8e3` | Numeric literal patterns |
| 4 | **Operators** | `+`, `-`, `*`, `/`, `=`, `==`, `<=`, `++` | Mathematical/logical symbols |
| 5 | **Special Symbols / Punctuators** | `;`, `,`, `(`, `)`, `{`, `}`, `[`, `]` | Punctuation characters |
| 6 | **String Literals** | `"hello"`, `"Kerala"` | Anything enclosed in double quotes |
| 7 | **Preprocessor Directives** | `#include`, `#define` | Lines beginning with `#` |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 High-Yield Point:** A common exam question asks *“What is the output of a lexical analyzer?”*. The correct answer is **a sequence of tokens (token-name, attribute-value) pairs**, **not** a parse tree or assembly code. Remembering this distinction can fetch full marks.

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Position of Lexical Analyzer in the Compiler Pipeline

The compiler is divided into two major halves:

$$
\boxed{\text{Analysis Phase (Front-End)} \;\;|\;\; \text{Synthesis Phase (Back-End)}}
$$

The **lexical analyzer** is the **first stage** of the **Analysis Phase**.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Source Program} \;\longrightarrow\; \text{Lexical Analyzer} \;\longrightarrow\; \text{Syntax Analyzer} \\
\;\longrightarrow\; \text{Semantic Analyzer} \;\longrightarrow\; \text{Intermediate Code Gen.} \\
\;\longrightarrow\; \text{Optimizer} \;\longrightarrow\; \text{Target Code Gen.}
\end{aligned}
$$

It reads the source as a raw character stream and outputs a **token stream** to the parser.

## 2.2 The Three Pillars: Token, Lexeme, Pattern

Let the input string be `int count = 100;`

| Lexeme | Token Name | Attribute Value |
|---|---|---|
| `int` | `<KEYWORD>` | (none) |
| `count` | `<IDENTIFIER>` | pointer to symbol table |
| `=` | `<OPERATOR, =>` | (none) |
| `100` | `<NUMBER>` | 100 |
| `;` | `<SYMBOL, ;>` | (none) |

The **Pattern** for `<IDENTIFIER>` in C is formally defined using a **Regular Expression**:

$$
\text{identifier} \rightarrow \text{letter} \mid \text{identifier letter} \mid \text{identifier digit}
$$

Or more compactly:

$$
\boxed{\text{identifier} = (a \mid b \mid \ldots \mid z \mid A \mid \ldots \mid Z \mid \_)\,(a \mid b \mid \ldots \mid z \mid A \mid \ldots \mid Z \mid 0 \mid \ldots \mid 9 \mid \_)^{*}}
$$

## 2.3 Why Separate Lexical Analysis from Parsing? (The "Why")

1. **Simplicity of Design** — The parser deals with token classes, not raw characters, drastically reducing its complexity.
2. **Efficiency** — Specialized buffering and pattern-matching techniques (e.g., DFA) make scanning very fast.
3. **Portability** — Input character-set, line-ending conventions, and special symbols can be isolated in the lexer.
4. **Better Error Reporting** — Line numbers and column positions are easier to maintain at the character level.

## 2.4 Algorithm: How the Lexer Recognizes a Token

The lexer uses a **Deterministic Finite Automaton (DFA)** for token recognition. The high-level logic is:

- **Step 1:** Read the next character `c` from the input buffer.
- **Step 2:** If `c` is whitespace or part of a comment → **skip and return to Step 1**.
- **Step 3:** If `c` is a letter or `_` → start buffer; read until non-alphanumeric; check if buffer matches a **keyword**; else emit `<IDENTIFIER>`.
- **Step 4:** If `c` is a digit → start buffer; read while digit (and optional decimal point); emit `<NUMBER>`.
- **Step 5:** If `c` is `"` → start string buffer; read until next `"`; emit `<STRING>`.
- **Step 6:** If `c` is an operator symbol → possibly peek next char for two-char operator; emit `<OPERATOR>`.
- **Step 7:** If `c` is a punctuator → emit `<SYMBOL>`.
- **Step 8:** If none of the above → **lexical error** (unrecognized character).

## 2.5 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| **Concept** | **Formal Notation** | **Example** |
|---|---|---|
| Lexeme | Actual matched string | `count` |
| Token | Pair $\langle \text{token-name}, \text{attribute} \rangle$ | $\langle \text{id}, \text{ptr} \rangle$ |
| Pattern | Rule (typically a Regular Expression) | `[A-Za-z\_][A-Za-z0-9\_]*` |
| Identifier | $(\text{letter}\mid\_)(\text{letter}\mid\text{digit}\mid\_)^{*}$ | `x`, `var_1` |
| Number | $\text{digit}^{+}\;(\,.\text{digit}^{+}\,)?$ | `100`, `3.14` |
| Comment (single line) | `//` followed by anything except newline | `// hello` |
| Comment (multi-line) | `/*` ... `*/` | `/* block */` |
| String | `"` (any char except `"`)* `"` | `"Kerala"` |

> [!TIP]
> **Engineering Real-World Use:** Lexical analyzers are the foundation of every modern tool you use — **GCC, Clang, Python's `tokenize` module, IDE syntax highlighters, code formatters, linters (like ESLint), and even search engines** that index source code. Designing one in C is the same logic used in production compilers, just without the optimization tricks (like Aho-Corasick for multi-pattern matching).

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# 3. Step-by-Step Implementation & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Complete C Program (KTU-Standard Implementation)

```c
/* ============================================================
 *  Experiment 2 : Lexical Analyzer (Scanner)
 *  Course       : PCCSL607 - Systems Lab (KTU 2024 Scheme)
 *  Author Style : Production-quality academic code
 * ============================================================ */
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <ctype.h>

#define MAX_LEN 100

/* ---------- Keyword Lookup Table ---------- */
const char *keywords[] = {
    "int", "float", "char", "double", "void", "long", "short",
    "if", "else", "while", "for", "do", "switch", "case",
    "default", "break", "continue", "return", "main",
    "printf", "scanf", "include", "define", "stdio"
};
const int KEYWORD_COUNT = sizeof(keywords) / sizeof(keywords[0]);

/* ---------- Helper : check if word is a keyword ---------- */
int isKeyword(char *word) {
    for (int i = 0; i < KEYWORD_COUNT; i++) {
        if (strcmp(word, keywords[i]) == 0)
            return 1;
    }
    return 0;
}

/* ============================================================
 *  MAIN DRIVER
 * ============================================================ */
int main(void) {
    FILE *fp;
    char filename[64];
    char ch, lookahead, buffer[MAX_LEN];
    int  idx;

    printf("Enter source file name : ");
    scanf("%63s", filename);

    fp = fopen(filename, "r");
    if (fp == NULL) {
        printf("\n[ERROR] Cannot open file : %s\n", filename);
        return EXIT_FAILURE;
    }

    printf("\n=========== LEXICAL ANALYSIS OUTPUT ===========\n");

    while ((ch = (char)fgetc(fp)) != EOF) {

        /* ---------- (A) Skip white space ---------- */
        if (ch == ' ' || ch == '\t' || ch == '\n' || ch == '\r')
            continue;

        /* ---------- (B) Skip comments ---------- */
        if (ch == '/') {
            lookahead = (char)fgetc(fp);

            if (lookahead == '/') {              /* // single-line */
                while ((ch = (char)fgetc(fp)) != EOF && ch != '\n')
                    ;   /* discard */
            }
            else if (lookahead == '*') {         /* /* ... */ block */
                while ((ch = (char)fgetc(fp)) != EOF) {
                    if (ch == '*' && (char)fgetc(fp) == '/')
                        break;
                }
            }
            else {                               /* genuine '/' operator */
                printf("<OPERATOR    , />\n");
                if (lookahead != EOF) ungetc(lookahead, fp);
            }
            continue;
        }

        /* ---------- (C) String literal ---------- */
        if (ch == '"') {
            idx = 0;
            buffer[idx++] = ch;
            while ((ch = (char)fgetc(fp)) != EOF && ch != '"')
                buffer[idx++] = ch;
            if (ch == '"') buffer[idx++] = ch;
            buffer[idx] = '\0';
            printf("<STRING      , %s>\n", buffer);
            continue;
        }

        /* ---------- (D) Identifier or Keyword ---------- */
        if (isalpha((unsigned char)ch) || ch == '_') {
            idx = 0;
            buffer[idx++] = ch;
            while ((ch = (char)fgetc(fp)) != EOF &&
                   (isalnum((unsigned char)ch) || ch == '_'))
                buffer[idx++] = ch;
            buffer[idx] = '\0';

            if (isKeyword(buffer))
                printf("<KEYWORD     , %s>\n", buffer);
            else
                printf("<IDENTIFIER  , %s>\n", buffer);

            if (ch != EOF) ungetc(ch, fp);
            continue;
        }

        /* ---------- (E) Numeric constant ---------- */
        if (isdigit((unsigned char)ch)) {
            idx = 0;
            buffer[idx++] = ch;
            int dotSeen = 0;
            while ((ch = (char)fgetc(fp)) != EOF) {
                if (isdigit((unsigned char)ch)) {
                    buffer[idx++] = ch;
                } else if (ch == '.' && !dotSeen) {
                    buffer[idx++] = ch;
                    dotSeen = 1;
                } else {
                    break;
                }
            }
            buffer[idx] = '\0';
            printf("<NUMBER      , %s>\n", buffer);
            if (ch != EOF) ungetc(ch, fp);
            continue;
        }

        /* ---------- (F) Two-character / one-character operators ---------- */
        if (strchr("=+-*/%<>&|!^", ch) != NULL) {
            lookahead = (char)fgetc(fp);
            /* Two-character operators: ==, !=, <=, >=, ++, --, &&, ||, <<, >>, +=, -=, etc. */
            if (  (ch == '=' && lookahead == '=') ||
                  (ch == '!' && lookahead == '=') ||
                  (ch == '<' && (lookahead == '=' || lookahead == '<')) ||
                  (ch == '>' && (lookahead == '=' || lookahead == '>')) ||
                  (ch == '+' && (lookahead == '+' || lookahead == '=')) ||
                  (ch == '-' && (lookahead == '-' || lookahead == '=')) ||
                  (ch == '*' && lookahead == '=') ||
                  (ch == '/' && lookahead == '=') ||
                  (ch == '%' && lookahead == '=') ||
                  (ch == '&' && (lookahead == '&' || lookahead == '=')) ||
                  (ch == '|' && (lookahead == '|' || lookahead == '=')) ||
                  (ch == '^' && lookahead == '=') ) {
                printf("<OPERATOR    , %c%c>\n", ch, lookahead);
            } else {
                printf("<OPERATOR    , %c>\n", ch);
                if (lookahead != EOF) ungetc(lookahead, fp);
            }
            continue;
        }

        /* ---------- (G) Preprocessor directive symbol ---------- */
        if (ch == '#') {
            printf("<PREPROCESSOR, #>\n");
            continue;
        }

        /* ---------- (H) Punctuators / Special Symbols ---------- */
        if (strchr("();,{}[]", ch) != NULL) {
            printf("<SYMBOL      , %c>\n", ch);
            continue;
        }

        /* ---------- (I) Unrecognized character ---------- */
        printf("<LEXICAL ERROR, '%c' [0x%02X]>\n", ch, (unsigned char)ch);
    }

    fclose(fp);
    printf("================================================\n");
    printf("Lexical Analysis Completed Successfully.\n");
    return EXIT_SUCCESS;
}
```

## 3.2 Sample Input File (`input.c`)

```c
#include <stdio.h>
int main()
{
    int a = 10;
    float b = 3.14;       // single line comment
    /* Multi-line
       block comment */
    if (a >= b) {
        a = a + 1;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

