## 3.4 Analytical Walkthrough — Why each character is classified this way

| Character Encountered | Branch Triggered in Code | Output Produced |
|---|---|---|
| `i`, `n`, `t`... forming `int` | `isalpha()` true → buffer fill → `isKeyword()` true | `<KEYWORD, int>` |
| `a` (after int) | `isalpha()` true → buffer fill → `isKeyword()` false | `<IDENTIFIER, a>` |
| `=` | Falls in `strchr("=+-*/%...")` | `<OPERATOR, =>` |
| `1`, `0` (digits) | `isdigit()` true → buffer fill | `<NUMBER, 10>` |
| `/` followed by `/` | `if (ch == '/')` + `lookahead == '/'` | Comment ignored |
| `/` followed by `*` | `lookahead == '*'` | Block comment ignored |
| `>`, `=` forming `>=` | Two-character operator match | `<OPERATOR, >=>` |
| `"`, `K`, ... `"` | `ch == '"'` branch | `<STRING, "Hello">` |
| `;` | `strchr("();,{}[]")` true | `<SYMBOL, ;>` |

> [!TIP]
> **Why `ungetc()` is critical:** When we read one character *ahead* to check for a two-character operator, we may have consumed a character that belongs to the **next** token. The standard C function `ungetc()` pushes that character back into the file stream buffer so the next iteration can process it correctly.

## 3.5 Common Pitfalls and Their Fixes (Trace Table)

| **Bug** | **Symptom** | **Fix** |
|---|---|---|
| Forgetting `ungetc(ch, fp)` | Next token missing its first char | Always rewind non-matching lookahead |
| Single-line comment not skipping `\n` | Comment swallows next line | Loop until `ch == '\n'` or `EOF` |
| Block comment not exiting on `*/` | Infinite loop | Break when `*` is followed by `/` |
| Using `==` inside the operator set | Treating `=` as a two-char always | Branch logic on `ch == '='` first, then check lookahead |
| String literal swallows newline | Lexer never recovers | Limit string scan to next `"` only |

