### `Q4. Question B (14 Marks)` `[KTU University Exam – Jul 2024, PCCSL607 — Alternative Choice]`

**(a)** With a neat **block diagram**, describe the **complete phases of a compiler** and explain the role of the lexical analyzer as the first phase. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Consider the following C source code. Show the **lexical analyzer output** (token stream) and identify any **lexical errors** if present. The lexer must handle `==`, `>=`, `++`, `/*` comments, and `//` comments. **(7 marks)**

```c
int main() {
    int x = 10;
    /* initialize y */
    int y == 20;        // note the double equal
    x++;
    if (x >= y) {
        x = x $ y;      // '$' is invalid
    }
}
```

### Model Solution

**(a) Compiler Phases and Role of Lexical Analyzer (7 marks):**

The compiler has **two main divisions**:
- **Analysis (Front-End):** Lexical → Syntax → Semantic → Intermediate Code Generation
- **Synthesis (Back-End):** Optimization → Target Code Generation

```
Source ──▶ [Lexical Analyzer] ──▶ [Syntax Analyzer] ──▶ [Semantic] ──▶ [ICG] ──▶ [Optimizer] ──▶ [TCG] ──▶ Target
                  │                    │                    │           │
                  ▼                    ▼                    ▼           ▼
              [Symbol Table] ◀────────┴────────────────────┴───────────┘
```

The **lexical analyzer** sits at the input boundary, consumes raw characters, and produces a clean token stream. It also maintains the **symbol table** which is shared with later phases. (A complete block diagram earns full 7 marks if all six phases and the symbol table are shown.)

**(b) Token Stream Output (7 marks):**

