> **Note on `y == 20`:** The lexical analyzer **will accept this** and emit `<OPERATOR, ==>`. It is a **syntax error**, NOT a lexical error, because `==` is a valid C token. The lexer does not know that the programmer probably meant `=`. This is a classic exam trap.

> **Note on `$`:** The `$` character is **not** part of C's operator/punctuator set, so the lexer correctly flags it as a **lexical error**.

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Pitfalls — Where You Lose Marks:**
> 1. **Conflating "lexical error" with "syntax error"** — A lexer detects invalid characters and malformed tokens (e.g., `123abc` where it expected a number, or stray `$`). It does NOT detect missing semicolons or invalid statement structure — that is the parser.
> 2. **Forgetting to handle `ungetc()` for lookahead** — Most students forget to rewind the file pointer after peeking. KTU valuators specifically check for this.
> 3. **Not distinguishing `=` (assignment) from `==` (equality)** — Make sure the program emits them as separate tokens with correct category names.
> 4. **Mixing up "lexeme" and "token" terminology** in theory answers — Use the exact words from Aho-Sethi-Ullman as KTU follows that textbook.
> 5. **Treating `stdio.h` as a single token** — Actually, in `#include <stdio.h>`, the `<` and `>` and `.` are separate symbols; only the file name forms a string-like token. Many students write it incorrectly.

