## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **High-Density Rapid-Revision Checklist (Pin this before exam):**

- **Lexical Analyzer = First phase of compiler**; input is character stream, output is token stream.
- A **Token** is `<token-name, attribute-value>` — for example, `<IDENTIFIER, ptr_to_symtab>`.
- A **Lexeme** is the actual matched substring; a **Pattern** is the rule for matching.
- The lexer is implemented as a **DFA (Deterministic Finite Automaton)** in production compilers.
- Identifier pattern: `letter (letter | digit | _)*`
- Number pattern: `digit+ (. digit+)?`
- Operators are categorized into **single-char and two-char** — always use `ungetc()` when peeking.
- Comments (`//` and `/* */`) and **whitespace** (space, tab, newline, carriage return) are **discarded**, not emitted.
- The lexer also maintains a **Symbol Table** for identifier storage.
- The lexer handles **line numbers** for error reporting — track them in a counter.
- **Common KTU 2-mark questions:** "Define token", "Differentiate lexeme vs token", "List compiler phases", "What does a lexer output?".
- **Common 7/14-mark questions:** "Write a C program to implement a lexical analyzer", "Show token stream for a given C snippet", "Explain the role and design of a lexical analyzer with a block diagram".
- **Mnemonic:** "**L**exers **L**ove **L**ists" — they read Characters → **Lexemes** → **Tokens** → forward to Parser.
- **Tool Mapping:** Real-world equivalents are `lex`, `flex`, `ANTLR` (lexer-generator tools) — your C program is the manual equivalent of what these tools auto-generate.

